el">Statement</th><td class=3D"infobox-data">The scaled sum of a sequence o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_and_identically_dist=
ributed_random_variables" title=3D"Independent and identically distributed =
random variables">i.i.d. random variables</a> with finite positive <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance" title=3D"Variance">variance</a>=
 converges in distribution to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a>.=
</td></tr><tr><th scope=3D"row" class=3D"infobox-label">Generalizations</th=
><td class=3D"infobox-data"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lindeb=
erg%27s_condition" title=3D"Lindeberg's condition"> Lindeberg's CLT</a></td=
></tr></tbody></table>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D=
"Probability theory">probability theory</a>, the <b>central limit theorem</=
b> (<b>CLT</b>) states that, under appropriate conditions, the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability=
 distribution">distribution</a> of a normalized version of the sample mean =
converges to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution=
#Standard_normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">standard norma=
l distribution</a>. This holds even if the original variables themselves ar=
e not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=
=3D"Normal distribution">normally distributed</a>. There are several versio=
ns of the CLT, each applying in the context of different conditions.
</p><p>The theorem is a key concept in probability theory because it implie=
s that probabilistic and statistical methods that work for normal distribut=
ions can be applicable to many problems involving other types of distributi=
ons.
</p><p>This theorem has seen many changes during the formal development of =
probability theory. Previous versions of the theorem date back to 1811, but=
 in its modern form it was only precisely stated in the 1920s.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-FOOTNOTEFischer2011[[Category:Wikipedia_articles_needing_page_number=
_citations_from_July_2023]]&lt;sup_class=3D&quot;noprint_Inline-Template_&q=
uot;_style=3D&quot;white-space:nowrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;&lt;i&gt;[[Wikiped=
ia:Citing_sources|&lt;span_title=3D&quot;This_citation_requires_a_reference=
_to_the_specific_page_or_range_of_pages_in_which_the_material_appears.&amp;=
#32;(July_2023)&quot;&gt;page&amp;nbsp;needed&lt;/span&gt;]]&lt;/i&gt;&amp;=
#93;&lt;/sup&gt;_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFischer2011[[Category:Wikip=
edia_articles_needing_page_number_citations_from_July_2023]]%3Csup_class=3D=
%22noprint_Inline-Template_%22_style=3D%22white-space:nowrap;%22%3E&amp;#91=
;%3Ci%3E[[Wikipedia:Citing_sources|%3Cspan_title=3D%22This_citation_require=
s_a_reference_to_the_specific_page_or_range_of_pages_in_which_the_material_=
appears.&amp;#32;(July_2023)%22%3Epage&amp;nbsp;needed%3C/span%3E]]%3C/i%3E=
&amp;#93;%3C/sup%3E-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Sta=
tistics">statistics</a>, the CLT can be stated as: let <span class=3D"mwe-m=
