een theorem</a>). <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stein%27s_method=
" title=3D"Stein's method">Stein's method</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-stein1972_=
21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_=
limit_theorem#cite_note-stein1972-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> can be used not only to p=
rove the central limit theorem, but also to provide bounds on the rates of =
convergence for selected metrics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-=
22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>The convergence to the normal distribution is monotonic, in the sens=
e that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_entropy" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Information entropy">entropy</a> of <span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-math=
ml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"htt=
p://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\textstyle Z_{n}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>Z</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\textstyle Z_{n}}</annotati=
on>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b6bb2f366f0fced92341046f7bdc5669190382a1" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.806ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\textstyle Z_{n}}=
"></span> increases <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotonic_func=
tion" title=3D"Monotonic function">monotonically</a> to that of the normal =
distribution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ABBN_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-ABBN-23"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>The central limit theorem applies in particular to sums of independe=
nt and identically distributed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dis=
crete_random_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discrete random varia=
ble">discrete random variables</a>.  A sum of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Discrete_random_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discre=
te random variable">discrete random variables</a> is still a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_random_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Discrete random variable">discrete random variable</a>, so that we=
 are confronted with a sequence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Discrete_random_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discrete random v=
ariable">discrete random variables</a> whose cumulative probability distrib=
ution function converges towards a cumulative probability distribution func=
tion corresponding to a continuous variable (namely that of the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribu=
tion">normal distribution</a>).  This means that if we build a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histogram" title=3D"Histogram">histogram</a> o=
f the realizations of the sum of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">n</span> independent identical discrete variables, the piec=
ewise-linear curve that joins the centers of the upper faces of the rectang=
les forming the histogram converges toward a Gaussian curve as <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> approaches infinity=
; this relation is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Moi=
vre%E2%80%93Laplace_theorem" title=3D"De Moivre=E2=80=93Laplace theorem">de=
 Moivre=E2=80=93Laplace theorem</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Binomial_distribution" title=3D"Binomial distribution">binomial dist=
ribution</a> article details such an application of the central limit theor=
em in the simple case of a discrete variable taking only two possible value=
s.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Common_misconceptions">Comm=
on misconceptions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DCentral_limit_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Common misconceptions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Studies have shown that the central limit theorem is subject to several =
common but serious misconceptions, some of which appear in widely used text=
books.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ce=
ntral_limit_theorem#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theor=
em#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These include:=20
</p>
<ul><li>The misconceived belief that the theorem applies to random sampling=
 of any variable, rather than to the mean values (or sums) of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iid" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Iid">iid</a=
> random variables extracted from a population by repeated sampling. That i=
s, the theorem assumes the random sampling produces a sampling distribution=
 formed from different values of means (or sums) of such random variables.<=
/li>
<li>The misconceived belief that the theorem ensures that random sampling l=
eads to the emergence of a normal distribution for sufficiently large sampl=
es of any random variable, regardless of the population distribution. In re=
ality, such sampling asymptotically reproduces the properties of the popula=
tion, an intuitive result underpinned by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Glivenko%E2%80%93Cantelli_theorem" title=3D"Glivenko=E2=80=93Can=
telli theorem">Glivenko=E2=80=93Cantelli theorem</a>.</li>
<li>The misconceived belief that the theorem leads to a good approximation =
of a normal distribution for sample sizes greater than around 30,<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> allowing reliable inference=
s regardless of the nature of the population. In reality, this empirical ru=
le of thumb has no valid justification, and can lead to seriously flawed in=
ferences. See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z-test" title=3D"Z-t=
est">Z-test</a> for where the approximation holds.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Relation_to_the_law_of_larg=
e_numbers">Relation to the law of large numbers</h3><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCentral_limit_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Relation to the law of large numb=
ers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_large_numbers" title=
=3D"Law of large numbers">law of large numbers</a> as well as the central l=
imit theorem are partial solutions to a general problem: "What is the limit=
ing behavior of <span class=3D"texhtml">S<sub><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span></sub></span> as <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> approaches infinity?" In math=
ematical analysis, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asymptotic_seri=
es" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Asymptotic series">asymptotic series</a>=
 are one of the most popular tools employed to approach such questions.
</p><p>Suppose we have an asymptotic expansion of <span class=3D"mwe-math-e=
lement mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-m=
