istribution" title=3D"Stable distribution">stable</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central=
_limit_theorem#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  Clearly, the normal distribution =
is stable, but there are also other stable distributions, such as the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cauchy_distribution" title=3D"Cauchy di=
stribution">Cauchy distribution</a>, for which the mean or variance are not=
 defined.  The scaling factor <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">b<sub>n</sub></span> may be proportional to <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n<sup>c</sup></span>, for any <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i> =E2=89=A5 <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-s=
tyle" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=
=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-on=
ly">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span>; it =
may also be multiplied by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slowly=
_varying_function" title=3D"Slowly varying function">slowly varying functio=
n</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Uchaikin_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-Uchaikin-30"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_the_iterated_log=
arithm" title=3D"Law of the iterated logarithm">law of the iterated logarit=
hm</a> specifies what is happening "in between" the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_large_numbers" title=3D"Law of large numbers">law =
of large numbers</a> and the central limit theorem. Specifically it says th=
at the normalizing function <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">=
