g log <i>n</i></span></span></span>, intermediate in size between <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> of the law of lar=
ge numbers and <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=88=9A<spa=
n style=3D"border-top:1px solid; padding:0 0.1em;"><i>n</i></span></span></=
span> of the central limit theorem, provides a non-trivial limiting behavio=
r.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Alternative_statements_of_t=
he_theorem">Alternative statements of the theorem</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCentral_limit_theorem&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Alternative statements of the t=
heorem"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Density_functions">Density =
functions</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCe=
ntral_limit_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Density functions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_density_functio=
n" title=3D"Probability density function">density</a> of the sum of two or =
more independent variables is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Convolution" title=3D"Convolution">convolution</a> of their densities (if t=
hese densities exist).  Thus the central limit theorem can be interpreted a=
s a statement about the properties of density functions under convolution: =
the convolution of a number of density functions tends to the normal densit=
y as the number of density functions increases without bound. These theorem=
s require stronger hypotheses than the forms of the central limit theorem g=
iven above. Theorems of this type are often called local limit theorems. Se=
e Petrov<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> for a par=
ticular local limit theorem for sums of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Independent_and_identically_distributed_random_variables" title=3D"In=
dependent and identically distributed random variables">independent and ide=
ntically distributed random variables</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Characteristic_functions">C=
haracteristic functions</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DCentral_limit_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=
=3D"Edit section: Characteristic functions"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Since the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characteristic_functi=
on_(probability_theory)" title=3D"Characteristic function (probability theo=
ry)">characteristic function</a> of a convolution is the product of the cha=
racteristic functions of the densities involved, the central limit theorem =
has yet another restatement: the product of the characteristic functions of=
 a number of density functions becomes close to the characteristic function=
 of the normal density as the number of density functions increases without=
 bound, under the conditions stated above. Specifically, an appropriate sca=
ling factor needs to be applied to the argument of the characteristic funct=
ion.
</p><p>An equivalent statement can be made about <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Fourier_transform" title=3D"Fourier transform">Fourier trans=
forms</a>, since the characteristic function is essentially a Fourier trans=
form.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Calculating_the_variance">C=
alculating the variance</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DCentral_limit_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=
=3D"Edit section: Calculating the variance"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S<sub>n</s=
ub></span> be the sum of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">n</span> random variables. Many central limit theorems provide cond=
itions such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">S<sub>n</sub></span>/<span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=88=
=9A<span style=3D"border-top:1px solid; padding:0 0.1em;">Var(<span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S<sub>n</sub></span>)</span>=
</span></span> converges in distribution to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>N</i=
>(0,1)</span> (the normal distribution with mean 0, variance 1) as <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n=
</span> =E2=86=92 =E2=88=9E</span>. In some cases, it is possible to find a=
 constant <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=83</i><sup>2</sup></span> and func=
tion <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f(n)</span> =
such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
