<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Regression">Regression</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCentral_limit_th=
eorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Regression=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis" title=3D"R=
egression analysis">Regression analysis</a>, and in particular <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_least_squares" title=3D"Ordinary leas=
t squares">ordinary least squares</a>, specifies that a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dependent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"De=
pendent variable">dependent variable</a> depends according to some function=
 upon one or more <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_vari=
able" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Independent variable">independent vari=
ables</a>, with an additive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Errors=
_and_residuals_in_statistics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Errors and res=
iduals in statistics">error term</a>. Various types of statistical inferenc=
e on the regression assume that the error term is normally distributed. Thi=
s assumption can be justified by assuming that the error term is actually t=
he sum of many independent error terms; even if the individual error terms =
are not normally distributed, by the central limit theorem their sum can be=
 well approximated by a normal distribution.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_illustrations">Other =
illustrations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DCentral_limit_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit =
section: Other illustrations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Illustration_of_the_=
central_limit_theorem" title=3D"Illustration of the central limit theorem">=
Illustration of the central limit theorem</a></div>
<p>Given its importance to statistics, a number of papers and computer pack=
ages are available that demonstrate the convergence involved in the central=
 limit theorem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Marasinghe_47-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-Maras=
inghe-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCentral_limit_theorem&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Dutch mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henk_Tijms"=
 title=3D"Henk Tijms">Henk Tijms</a> writes:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tijms_48-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit=
_theorem#cite_note-Tijms-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The central limit theorem has an int=
eresting history. The first version of this theorem was postulated by the F=
rench-born mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_d=
e_Moivre" title=3D"Abraham de Moivre">Abraham de Moivre</a> who, in a remar=
kable article published in 1733, used the normal distribution to approximat=
e the distribution of the number of heads resulting from many tosses of a f=
air coin. This finding was far ahead of its time, and was nearly forgotten =
until the famous French mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pierre-Simon Laplace">Pierre-Simon Lapla=
ce</a> rescued it from obscurity in his monumental work <i>Th=C3=A9orie ana=
lytique des probabilit=C3=A9s</i>, which was published in 1812.  Laplace ex=
panded De Moivre's finding by approximating the binomial distribution with =
the normal distribution. But as with De Moivre, Laplace's finding received =
little attention in his own time. It was not until the nineteenth century w=
as at an end that the importance of the central limit theorem was discerned=
, when, in 1901, Russian mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Aleksandr_Lyapunov" title=3D"Aleksandr Lyapunov">Aleksandr Lyapunov</a=
> defined it in general terms and proved precisely how it worked mathematic=
ally. Nowadays, the central limit theorem is considered to be the unofficia=
l sovereign of probability theory.</p></blockquote>
<p>Sir <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Galton" title=3D"Fr=
ancis Galton">Francis Galton</a> described the Central Limit Theorem in thi=
s way:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>I know of scarcely anyth=
ing so apt to impress the imagination as the wonderful form of cosmic order=
 expressed by the "Law of Frequency of Error". The law would have been pers=
onified by the Greeks and deified, if they had known of it. It reigns with =
serenity and in complete self-effacement, amidst the wildest confusion. The=
 huger the mob, and the greater the apparent anarchy, the more perfect is i=
ts sway. It is the supreme law of Unreason. Whenever a large sample of chao=
tic elements are taken in hand and marshalled in the order of their magnitu=
de, an unsuspected and most beautiful form of regularity proves to have bee=
n latent all along.</p></blockquote>
<p>The actual term "central limit theorem" (in German: "zentraler Grenzwert=
satz") was first used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_P%=
C3%B3lya" title=3D"George P=C3=B3lya">George P=C3=B3lya</a> in 1920 in the =
title of a paper.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Polya1920_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-Poly=
a1920-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-LC1986_51-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-LC1=
986-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> P=C3=B3lya referred to the theorem as "central" due to =
its importance in probability theory. According to Le Cam, the French schoo=
l of probability interprets the word <i>central</i> in the sense that "it d=
escribes the behaviour of the centre of the distribution as opposed to its =
tails".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-LC1986_51-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-LC1986-51"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> The abstract of the paper <i>On the central limit theorem of calculus=
 of probability and the problem of moments</i> by P=C3=B3lya<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Polya1920_50-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#cite_note-Polya1920-50"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> in 1920 tr=
anslates as follows.
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The occurrence of the Ga=
ussian probability density <span class=3D"texhtml">1 =3D <i>e</i><sup>=E2=
=88=92<i>x</i><sup>2</sup></sup></span> in repeated experiments, in errors =
of measurements, which result in the combination of very many and very smal=
l elementary errors, in diffusion processes etc., can be explained, as is w=
ell-known, by the very same limit theorem, which plays a central role in th=
e calculus of probability. The actual discoverer of this limit theorem is t=
o be named Laplace; it is likely that its rigorous proof was first given by=
 Tschebyscheff and its sharpest formulation can be found, as far as I am aw=
are of, in an article by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aleksandr=
_Lyapunov" title=3D"Aleksandr Lyapunov">Liapounoff</a>. ...</p></blockquote=
>
<p>A thorough account of the theorem's history, detailing Laplace's foundat=
ional work, as well as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustin-Lo=
uis_Cauchy" title=3D"Augustin-Louis Cauchy">Cauchy</a>'s, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Bessel" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fr=
iedrich Bessel">Bessel</a>'s and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
im%C3%A9on_Denis_Poisson" title=3D"Sim=C3=A9on Denis Poisson">Poisson</a>'s=
 contributions, is provided by Hald.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hald_52-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem#=
cite_note-Hald-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Two historical accounts, one covering the de=
velopment from Laplace to Cauchy, the second the contributions by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_von_Mises" title=3D"Richard von M=
ises">von Mises</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_P%C3%B=
3lya" title=3D"George P=C3=B3lya">P=C3=B3lya</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Jarl_Waldemar_Lindeberg" title=3D"Jarl Waldemar Lindeberg">=
Lindeberg</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_L%C3%A9vy_(mat=
